Written evidence submitted by Community Law Partnership (JRR 0002)default&#xa0;defaultWe make this submission further to our previous general submission and previous evidence submission to the Inquiry and in respons
defaulte to the further call for evidence with regard to the Ministry of Justice consultation paper 
defaultJudicial Review: proposals for further reform
default. As explained in our submission to Lord McNally ( see annex to this paper), we are very concerned at the sudden appea
defaultrance in the latest consultation paper of a proposal to refer all planning appeals to tribunal and to remove legal aid from appeals under sections 288 &amp; 289 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990.We are concerned that this proposal may ‘go under the rad
defaultar’ especially because many people may not realise that virtually the only (if not 
defaultthe onlydefault) groups that will be adversely affected will be Gypsies and Travellers. We give details here of three cases that show the importance of 
defaultss
default 288 &amp; 289 cases for Gypsi
defaultes and Travellers and the importance of the availability of legal aid in such cases.  
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
defaultBefore Ms Moore moved to the appeal site in July 2010 she and her children lived for some 12 years in a caravan situated on the front drive of a rented Ho
defaultusing Association property in Orpington.  This was due to the fact that she had an aversion to living in bricks and mortar accommodation.  The Housing Association in March 2010 gave Ms 
defaultM
defaultoore a 28 days’ Notice to remove the vehicles from her drive and later
default a further Notice was sent regarding the Association seeking legal advice on the matter.  Ms Moore had submitted an application for planning permission for her site which already had the benefit of permission for equestrian use.  In July 2010 Ms Moore, tog
defaultether with her children, moved onto the site with her mobile home and her tenancy with the Housing Association was terminated.  The local planning authority (LPA) refused her application for change of use and they then commenced injunction proceedings in l
defaultate 2010 which have been stayed pending the outcome of her appeal.  The refusal of planning permission was appealed to the Planning Inspectorate and the Inspector went on to dismiss her planning appeal.
default&#xa0;
defaultHad legal aid not been available for a Section 288 T
defaultown &amp; Country Planning Act (T&amp;CPA) 1990 application to the high court, then that would have brought the matter to an end.  The LPA would have proceeded with its application for an injunction under Section 187B of the T&amp;CPA 1990 and by now Ms Moore would be
default off the land.
default&#xa0;
defaultMs Moore then lodged her challenge to the Inspector’s dismissal of her appeal and counsel was then instructed on the matter.  Judgment was handed down by Mrs Justice Cox on 16 November 2012.  Mrs Justice Cox allowed the appeal and gave a ve
defaultry lengthy and reasoned judgment.  She found that the Inspector failed to make relevant findings, as required, and that his decision to refuse a temporary planning permission to Ms Moore was irrational and could not stand.  Alternatively, she considered th
defaultat the Inspector’s decision on the issue of temporary permission was inadequately reasoned and that, for that reason in addition, his decision could not stand.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Secretary of State then appealed to the Court of Appeal who upheld the decision of Mrs Just
defaultice Cox. Lord Justice Richards emphasised the importance of taking into account 
defaultthe fact that the family would have had to resort to roadside camping if they did not receive temporary planning permission. This is an important decision not just for Ms Moore
default but for all Gypsies and Travellers who are seeking at least temporary permission while they wait for local planning authorities to produce their five year deliverable supply of sites (which they should already have done under the DCLG’s new planning polic
defaulty 
defaultPlanning policy for traveller sites
default). Once again this important decision (not only for our client but for other Gypsies and Travellers) would not have been achieved without the availability of legal aid.     
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;defaultThis is now the leading authority on the approach to Gypsy and Traveller sites in the context of Green Belt policy. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn
default this case the Appellants, Kathleen and Leonard Butler, were Romani Gypsies who lived on their own land in the Green Belt with their two young children. 
defaultWychavon
default District Council refused their application for planning permission since they said it constitu
defaultted inappropriate development within the Green Belt. That decision was then appealed by way of a Section 78 Appeal to the Planning Inspectorate and on appeal the Planning Inspector granted Mr and Mrs Butler a temporary planning permission of five years. Pl
defaultanning permission was granted for a number of reasons and these related to the family’s educational and health needs, and the current lack of alternative sites which all constituted ‘very special circumstances’. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe LPA appealed that decision to the high
default court and the judge hearing the Council’s appeal allowed it, holding that the factors which were identified by the Inspector were commonplace and could not amount to very special circumstances. This meant that the five year temporary planning permission w
defaulthich had been granted to Mr and Mrs Butler was taken away from them and then the matter would need to be remitted back to the Inspectorate for a fresh determination. 
default&#xa0;
defaultFortunately for Mr and Mrs Butler, with the benefit of public funding, an appeal was lod
defaultged with the Court of Appeal challenging the high court decision. The Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government consented to a judgment and was not represented at the final hearing in June 2008. The Secretary of State had not resisted the app
defaultlication to quash the decision. Although she was not a party to the appeal she had submitted a written statement in which she had only taken issue with a small part of the judge’s reasoning. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Court of Appeal handed down its decision on 23 June 2008. The Court of Appeal allowed the Appeal. The court held that the Judge below (and also Sullivan J in 
defaultR (Chelmsford BC) –v- The First Secretary of State 
default[2004] 2 P &amp; CR 677) had been wrong to appl
defaulty a two stage test, requiring both that there must be circumstances which can reasonably be described as very special and that the various types of harm had been clearly outweighed by other considerations. There was no such ‘rigid division’ and the word ‘s
defaultpecial’ in the guidance meant ‘not a quantitative test, but a qualitative Judgment as to weight to be given to the particular factor for planning purposes’. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn this case the judge in the high court had been wrong to quash as perverse the Inspector’s deci
defaultsion that there were very special circumstances such as to justify a temporary five year permission. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;defaultThis 
defaultcase was an application under Section 288 of T&amp;CPA 1990. The Inspector appointed by the Secretary of State had dismissed our client’s appeal against the refusal of planning permission. The site in question was in the Dorset Area of Outstanding Natural Beau
defaultty (AONB). The Inspector dismissed the appeal following a Public Inquiry and with the benefit of public funding an application under Section 288 was lodged with the high court. The Inspector’s decision was criticised on two main grounds: 
default&#xa0;
default1.
default              
defaultThe way in wh
defaultich the Inspector addressed the rights of Langton and McGill under Article 8;
default&#xa0;
default2.
default              
defaultThe Inspector’s treatment of the balance to be struck between the ‘need for sites’ which supported the grant of permission and the harm done to the AONB. 
defaultThe judge hearing t
defaulthis case rejected the first ground but upheld the second. The outcome of the case was that our appeal was upheld and the Inspector’s decision was quashed. When that decision was remitted back to the Planning Inspectorate, Langton and McGill were granted a 
defaulttemporary planning permission.
