defaultAnnexdefault&#xa0;defaultJUDICIAL REVIEW: PROPOSALS FOR FURTHER REFORMdefault&#xa0;defaultSUBMISSIONS OF LORD AVEBURY, BARONESS WHITAKER AND CHRIS JOHNSON ON THE IMPLICATIONS FOR GYPSIES AND TRAVELLERSdefault&#xa0;defaultWe are grateful to Lord McNally for giving us the 
defaultopportunity to meet him and put these submissions to him on 30
defaultth
default October 2013. At his request we have provided this summary of the submissions we put forward and we also mention certain other matters that were raised in the meeting.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe started with a quot
defaulte from former Lord Justice of Appeal, Stephen 
defaultSedley
default:
defaultIn the round, judicial review is an economic and effective branch of litigation performing a constitutionally critical role in keeping the exercise of public power within the law, and legal aid for it i
defaults for the most part money well spent.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultPlanningdefault&#xa0;defaultUnder the proposals there are two ways in which Gypsies and Travellers who are trying to get planning permission for their own land might be stopped from receiving legal aid for a planning appeal to the 
defaultHigh Court.
default&#xa0;
defaultSpecialist property chamber of the Upper Tribunaldefault&#xa0;defaultThe rationale behind this proposal is to cut down on delays caused to large developments. This is perfectly acceptable but individuals who need to take appeals should be excluded from this tra
defaultnsfer since there is no legal aid for tribunal representation.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt might be said that the ‘safety net’ of exceptional funding under LASPOA 2012 s10 is available to such individuals. However figures from the Legal Aid Practitioners Group show that, at the b
defaulteginning of September 2013 ( the new scheme having commenced in April 2013), out of 635 applications across England and covering all areas of law, only 11 had been granted. A Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request by Community Law Partnership (CLP) reve
defaultaled that only one grant was for a Housing Law case (Gypsy and Traveller cases come under this umbrella). 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe simple fact is that the vast majority of our clients will not be able to represent themselves: the literacy problems in the Gypsy and Traveller 
defaultcommunity are well known; many have not had a formal education or very little formal education; the law and procedures are extremely complex even if you have had a formal education.
default&#xa0;
defaultTown and Country Planning Act 1990 sections 288 &amp; 289default&#xa0;defaultThe bald proposal 
defaultto remove legal aid from such cases seems to target Romani Gypsies and Irish Travellers since it is very difficult to imagine which other individuals might receive legal aid for such appeals. CLP have put in a FOIA request on this issue.
default&#xa0;
defaultLord McNally info
defaultrmed us at the meeting that the Department for Communities and Local Government (DCLG) feel that the processes in place ( involving planning inspectors and sometimes the Secretary of State himself) are sufficient to guarantee good decisions without the nec
defaultessity of an appeal process. We responded as follows:
default(i)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere are many successful appeals (see the 
defaultMoore 
defaultcase as just one good example)  – so the process cannot be quite so sufficient as is stated;
default(ii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNo doubt county court judges, high court judges and others c
defaultarry out careful and detailed processes – yet there is an appeal mechanism against their decisions – why should Gypsies and Travellers yet again be singled out as not being entitled to have an appeal process?
default(iii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default What if the local authority appeals to the hig
defaulth court against the inspector’s decision in favour of the Gypsy or Traveller concerned – if the Gypsy or Traveller is not represented, the local authority are much more likely to succeed in their appeal.
default&#xa0;
defaultIf the Gypsy and Traveller concerned are successful
default, then their accommodation problems are resolved. This will have significant knock on implications on education, healthcare, job opportunities etc. On the other hand, if they are not successful they will end up on roadside encampments which involve expense
default for taxpayers in terms of eviction actions by local authorities. So, at the end of the day, there are not really any costs savings if legal aid is removed for such cases. 
default&#xa0;
defaultJudicial reviewdefault&#xa0;defaultThe fact is that most cases settle before permission is dealt 
defaultwith and that settlement is usually favourable to the claimant.
default&#xa0;
defaultAny such settlement does not mean that the claimant will get his/her costs. The public authority concerned might say they will settle but without conceding that the grounds of claim were just
defaultified.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis has led to the proposal that the Legal Aid Agency (LAA) should have a discretion to pay the costs when the case settles before permission is dealt with but without a costs award in favour of the claimant. Due to the way the LAA have dealt with
default exceptional funding applications and other matters, legal aid practitioners have absolutely no confidence that the LAA will grant costs in such cases. 
default&#xa0;
defaultJudicial review holds public authorities to account, leads to better decision making and leads to the 
defaultremoval of unlawful policies and practices.
default&#xa0;
defaultConclusiondefault&#xa0;defaultRemoval of legal aid in these cases (either directly or because legal aid lawyers will not be able to take the risk of running a case) will inevitably mean that many individuals in dire circumstances
default will be denied the right to a fair hearing and that unlawful actions and decisions by local authorities will go unchecked. These proposals will have a disproportionate impact on Gypsies and Travellers.
